node.text:
@thealpinistfilm is premiering in theaters on September 10th!
It’s an incredible film about Marc-André Leclerc and some of his mind boggling alpine solos. I’ve seen it a few times and have been deeply impressed each time - he was such a singular character in the climbing world. The film really does him justice. 
I strongly encourage anyone able to see the film in theaters - the landscapes that he visits deserve the biggest possible screen (much like Free Solo…)
I included a few of my own pics of Marc-André from Patagonia in 2015 or him soloing the Corkscrew route on Cerro Torre. They give a sense of the scale of things he was climbing. Zoom into the last pics to find the tiny black dot against the sky line… 
Link in bio to more info about how to get tickets.

node.text: I was recently involved in an interesting @thenorthface collaboration with @sonos and @sonosradio in which they turned the audio and sound effects from many of our expeditions over the years into creative songs. They're composed by Wilco's @mikaeljorgensen who worked with each of us on the various expeditions to craft songs unique to each trip. I didn't totally understand the idea when I heard about it, but then after I listened to the songs and helped record audio for them I got pretty into it. Some of the tracks are a major blast from the past for me - a super fun way to revisit some great expeditions. Worth checking out if you need some climbing inspired music! Link in bio.

node.text:
I learned with great sadness that David Roberts, the coauthor of my book Alone on the Wall, died on Friday after years of fending off cancer. The Boston Globe wrote a great obituary for him that does justice to his wide ranging writing and mountaineering accomplishments (32 books and something like 20 expeditions to Alaska?!?). I’ve only gotten to know him in his later years, post-alpine career, so I think of him foremost as an incredible writer and serious thinker. His emails often included little phrases in Latin or German or lines like “you know, when Beethoven was your age…”. I would typically have to look up at least one thing each time he wrote, which was part of the joy of knowing David - it’s rare to meet someone with such intellect. 
He was also the first person to take me golfing (and got me out twice!). 
It’s hard to fit all my thoughts in a caption. I guess it’s enough to say that I’ll miss David and I deeply appreciate the impact he had on my life. And I’m sending my love to Sharon, his lifelong wife and partner. 
I suppose more than most folks David will live on in his tremendous body of work, from new routes in Alaska to dozens of books on all kinds of subjects.  I guess I’ll just have to reread my favorites…
(All the photos are from David’s longtime friend Matt Hale, I borrowed them from the Globe obituary since they make David look great)

node.text:
Today’s sport climbing session turned out a lot more apocalyptic than we expected. This photo has no filter or effects - the sky is choked with wildfire smoke that blocked out the sun. I almost needed a headlamp on my last attempt. 
Having grown up in this area I’ve now spent 36 years adventuring around in these mountains - these kinds of wild fires simply didn’t happen 25 years ago. Heck, even 10 years ago this would have seemed unprecedented. 
The IPCC report last week made for some somber reading. Climate change is no longer a vague abstraction, you just have to look outside…
Also, thanks to everyone for all the birthday wishes, and to everyone who’s supported @honnoldfoundation today. It’s just an unusual kind of birthday when it’s raining ash outside… feeling grateful for all the folks fighting fires right now…
